    <subsection>
        <title>Multiplying and dividing fractions</title>
        <p>To double or half a recipe, we need to consider fractions of fractions. Say a recipe calls for ⅔ cup of milk, but we’d like to double it. Using rectangular sketches exactly how we’d use a measuring cup in life we have:</p>

        <todo>(two rectangles with ⅔ highlighted)</todo>

        <p>So ⅔ * 2 = 4/3. This sketch show ⅔ of two wholes. Two wholes can be written as 2, or as the fraction 2/1. So mathematically, our figure says ⅔ * 2 = ⅔ * 2/1 = 4/3.</p>

        <p>We can also see this on the number line:</p>

        <todo>(number line indicated two 2/3s)</todo>

        <p>The number line also shows that ⅔ * 2 = 4/3.</p>

        <p>We can also use multiplication to decrease amounts. How much is 1/2 of ⅔ cup? Looking at a sketch of ⅔:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketch showing ⅔)</todo>

        <p>We can “break” that in half like so:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketch showing 1/2 of ⅔)</todo>

        <p>So 1/2 of ⅔ cup is 2/6 cup. Mathematically, we can write ⅔ * 1/2 = 2/6.</p>

        <p>This idea works generally, no matter what amounts we use:
a/b * c/d = (ac) / (bd)</p>

        <p>Multiplication works when we ask about “How much is this fraction of that amount?” Division answers the question “How many of those amounts fit into that amount?”</p>

        <p>Suppose a baker lost their 1/3 cup measuring cup, and wanted to use a 1/2 cup measuring cup to measure out 2/3 cup of brown sugar. They’d need to answer “How many 1/2 cups are in ⅔ cup?” That is, they'd need to find 2/3 divided by 1/2. Let’s start by sketching amounts:
(sketch of ⅔, sketch of 1/2)
Remember that love for fractions depends on understanding which whole amount has our attention. When we ask “How many 1/2 cups are in ⅔ cup?” we are asking about a number of 1/2 cups. That means that the whole amount in this division problem is a 1/2 cup. Okay, let’s look back at the situation with both thirds and halves in the same picture:
(sketch of ⅔ with 1/2 as well)
Can you see how many halves are in ⅔?
(sketch of ⅔ with 1/2 labeled as “whole”)
There 4/3 halves in ⅔. That means that ⅔ div 1/2 = 4/3.</p>

        <p>If we look back at the sketch, and ask “How much is 2/1 of ⅔?” Looking carefully, we “see” that ⅔ * 2/1 = 4/3. We’ve sketched both division and multiplication in one sketch. If we love fractions enough, we can “see” that ⅔ div 1/2 = ⅔ * 2/1 = 4/3.</p>

        <p>This works no matter what amounts we use as well:
a/b div c/d = a/b div d/c = (ad)/(bc)</p>
